'''Kashima Miko Shrine''' (かしまみこじんじゃ) is a Shinto shrine in Kashima Ward, {{ill|lt=Minamisoma|Q642094|WD=Q642094}}, Fukushima Prefecture. Its former rank was gosha, and it is one of the eight Engishiki shrines of former Namekata District.

=== Enshrined deities ===
* Amatariwake-no-Mikoto (described as a child deity of Takemikazuchi; some theories identify with Ame-no-Koyane)
* Shinatsuhiko-no-Mikoto
* Shinatsuhime-no-Mikoto

=== Origin traditions ===
A regional tradition says Amatariwake descended to pacify evil in Oshu with Takemikazuchi, Futsunushi, and Asahiko. Shrine records state that after pacification Amatariwake remained here and this shrine was founded.

In the era of Emperor Keiko, Yamato Takeru prayed here for victory during eastern campaigns and succeeded, after which the shrine was especially revered by warriors as a war deity shrine.

The shrine originally stood about 200 m south of the current site and was moved to the present location in 806. A stone monument marks the former site. Historically, it had many clergy and shrine lands and received annual offerings from {{ill|lt=Kashima Jingu|Q706499|WD=Q706499}}.

In 905, it was counted among the Engishiki shrines of Mutsu, revered as a deity of war, fire-prevention, and healing. In 1635, Soma Yoshitane repaired buildings, donated ritual expenses and lands; patronage by Soma domain lords continued until the Meiji Restoration.

It was designated gosha in 1876 and became an officially visited offering shrine in 1926.

=== Special rite: Chinka-sai ===
A unique fire-quelling festival is held based on local legend.
* January 14: "Hibuse-sai" - youths run through town chanting fire-protection calls and sprinkle sacred water
* Early morning January 15: "Tentoro-sai" - rites at the former shrine site with songs and kagura; on return, priests are splashed with purified water, then perform annual purification and prayers for fire prevention

=== Precinct ===
* Main shrine buildings (haiden, heiden, honden)
* Kaname-ishi (foundation stone)
* Pair of giant zelkova trees ("Meoto Keyaki"), designated Fukushima natural monument in 2022
* Raijin Shrine (agricultural deity)
* Ashio Shrine (guiding deity; also prayed to for leg/foot healing)
* Prince Shotoku stone shrine
* Shrine office, ginkgo tree, war memorial, haiku stone

A corridor displays ema dedicated by volunteers who came to the area after the 2011 Great East Japan Earthquake for reconstruction and nuclear-disaster recovery prayers. The shrine also suffered damage, including collapse of a torii, in the 2022 offshore Fukushima earthquake.

=== Access ===
* 5 minutes on foot from JR Joban Line Kashima Station

